segments.text: Style, manner, physically.
As someone who wanted to get from point A to point B in the shortest time and got there.
He did not tolerate foolishness.
Spoke with great conviction.
And I suspect that at times he was less
certain than he appeared to be.
But again, I think one of the things that was very good about Earl Rudder was that even though he was not an academician, he knew what a good university was about.
And I think that he diligently saw people who could move A&M from where it was to where it needed to be.
At that time, we just had a lot of strong administrators.
Talk about Frank Hubert.
Fred Benson was very strong.
Again, time sort of faded, but agriculture was always strong with John Hutchison.
So just across the board A&M was staffed by very strong administrators.
Do you know of any individual or individuals that were part of the A&M campus
that were particularly influential with Mr. Ruddell?
I think Fred Benson.
I had an opportunity to sit on the Executive Committee for a while, and Fred Benson was the one who was most likely to openly differ with Earl Ruddell.
And Earl Rutter always seemed to respect Fred Benson's opinion and his guidance.
So I think he was the one who impressed me most of the time that I saw him, as far as being able to speak very directly with Earl Rutter.
Q Can you think of any important issues or decisions during Mr. Rutter's era that in second thought
if we had it to do over again, we would have done it differently?
Can you think of any decision that?
Well, the one that I think that I would like to have seen done differently.
I may be the lone ranger.
But with ANM's widespread system office that we have now in the university,
I thought one of the mistakes that was probably made at the time was the giving up of UT Arlington.
What's now UT Arlington was Arlington State College.
It was an engineering-oriented university in the Metroplex.
And I've been told that there may have been a lot of pressure from UT to get that.
My feeling at the time was that the faculty up there did not believe that A&M paid as much attention to UT Arlington as it deserved and that may or may not have been the case.
But I think A&M lost a real opportunity to have a major presence in the metroplex.
And that could be so significant today for many, many reasons.
I think so.
Again, there were others that were obviously value judgments, one that's much less important on the large scale.
But I thought the junction was something that was very unusual, if not unique, that A&M had to offer.
And again, it appeared to me
that junction was given up to Texas Tech with little reluctance and no resistance.

One of the things that, again, I thought was interesting, and I think there were some obvious reasons why, but at least my understanding was that when they got UT Galveston, they had an opportunity to have a presence of Corpus Christi at the same time.
And I think that was a very important decision.
What will prove to be best may still be in the future.
Were you aware that Mr. Rutter's health was declining before he became ill?
I was aware that he had gained a lot of weight.
It didn't appear his color was as good as it might be, but that was a very demanding job, physically, emotionally.
I suspected then and found out later as I was moving into so-called upper level administration that you get invited to a lot of meals.
For a lot of us it's hard to pass up that dessert, and we probably should, but I know that there were a lot of people who really believed
that having a combined present university and present system in one person was more than should be expected of any one human being.
Because it was very, very pressure-packed and very demanding.
But don't I recall that he, sometimes as president, was not in agreement with the system leadership and that he liked
getting it all under his... Oh, absolutely.
Absolutely.
And this is not quite a sequence, but I remember, again, going back to the cell study and my visiting with Jack Williams.
One of the first questions I asked him, because of the strong feeling people had about a combined job for one person being a killer, I asked Jack Williams what his thoughts were.
about having two separate offices.
And he was adamant that it should be one.

And I remember him telling me that there was only one thing that he knew of that worked, and that is in the Navy, that if you had an admiral of fleet aboard a ship, there was never any question that the captain of the ship ran the ship.
Admiral had nothing to do with the operation of the ship.
He said anytime you have the system offices on the campus of the flagship university, you've got problems because you've got end runs that are being constantly made.
And in essence, he wouldn't tolerate the idea of having the jobs separated.
So there were obvious reasons as to why the CEO wanted to have control of the
the system as well as the university because there is so much interaction between and among the agencies that it certainly makes the line of authority much clearer.
So do you remember any moment when you heard that Mr. Rutter was seriously ill or had died?
I remember it because I thought it was a catastrophic time for A&M.
I don't remember the specific moments.
When John Kennedy was shot, I remember walking out on the third floor of a G-Roller flight and hearing what I thought was a bad joke and finding out it was not.
It was just bad.
Let's do that just a second.
And what did you, what followed that, what did you do when you heard that that was the truth?
I went back to my office and got a radio and started listening to all the news reports that I could get.
And like I said, I remember most vividly that I was playing badminton at night.
And walked out, and this was about deer season time, and I thought this is one of those really sick jokes.
And then of course had the decision to make about bonfire and some other things.

So it was a, as a native Dallasite, I was very defensive about Dallas being branded as that radical, and I still remain somewhat bitter about people branding the whole city for something that someone who was not even a resident of the city doing.
And you knew all of the locations.
All of the locations.
You knew where those were.
With Mr. Rutter, we then had an interim president.
Al Ludeke.
Al Ludeke.
And then Williams was selected.
How did you hear, do you remember anything that you heard?
Were you aware of a search process or anything?
I was aware of a search process.
And I had heard a little bit that Jack Williams was a strong candidate.
But I would like to say just a few words.
I had a lot of admiration for Al Lutie.
Oh, please, yes, yes.
I thought he came into a very, very awkward situation.
He and Earl Rutter were classmates, as I understand it, from the same general part of Texas.
Same type of military record, in that they were both generals, not the combat record.
There was a lot of suspicion among the faculty about, you know, here's another class of 32 from West Texas in general.
And again, Al Ludeke was someone who was not a dynamic speaker.
I think he realized that, and so I think he viewed his public addresses as a chore to be endured.
And he spoke very
succinctly, and had a lot of thought in what he said.
So he was one of those who would stand up, speak up, and shut up.
And I think a lot of people admired that.
And I think that he gained a lot of respect from a lot of backers pretty quickly.
And then when Jack Williams came in, Al Ludigant worked with the system planning and did a very good job with that as well.
So for a transition president, I thought A&M could not have made a better choice than they did.
And then I think Jack Williams was, by my definition, the second man for his time at A&M.
He took A&M from the point that Earl Rudder had brought it to make it really a pretty comprehensive university.
You're back as, at this point, you're back as the associate?
No, I'm now in the Vice President's office.
One of the recommendations that came out of the cell study was to have an office of planning.
And so that became a major factor.
Charlie Bunnell had done some work in the general area before I got there.
But worked with planning and then became an associate vice president.
How did that search process
I don't know if there was a certain process.
Who contacted you?
John Calhoun.
Describe Calhoun and his style.
It sounds like I'm polishing the apple, but there's so many that I just have a lot of admiration for, and John Calhoun is certainly in that category.
I'll tell you one other aside.
My first wife, Joyce, had been part-time secretary in John Calhoun's office when he was in the system office.
And one of the things, she always liked him a lot, but one of the stories she told me that just really amazed her was that someone asked him for a list of the top five people in the serving field.
And the first one he put on the list was John C. Calhoun Jr. And Joyce said, you know, it wasn't, he was bragging.
He would just ask to rank them, and he was in the top five.
And most of us are not that self-assured that we can do that.
But he's very bright, and I think he has a good sense of humor that is not evident to everyone.
For the people who are around him, he's jovial.
He's outgoing.
And one of the things that, again, is of no consequence, but I enjoyed it at least, was that there was a very rapid turnover of the secretarial staff in the Vice President's office.
Oftentimes he'd just refer to someone in the politically, now politically incorrect way of saying, the new girl.
At one point, someone made up a little desk sign and said, the new girl.
Put that as a name plate on the girl.
Then they wound up with the newest girl.
But John Calhoun, again, is one of those who can give you authority and responsibility.
And I think you learn quickly.
that you better be very careful what you suggest, because it may come to pass.
And if you haven't thought it through pretty carefully, it's not going to go over well with anybody.
And so I think if I'm going to say something to him, I better be pretty sure of what I'm going to say.
John Calhoun has a lot of thoughts, and I'll jump way back.
But Frank Hubert has a truly creative mind.
And I'll come back to John Kelly, but one story that I'd like to get on the record.
On the Harrington Building, in the classroom portion, Frank Hubert spent a lot of time thinking about a truly technologically advanced series of classrooms.
And some of the things that he thought were so good in theory, but didn't work well in practice.
The Harrington classroom building was designed that people would enter at the back of the room.
And then the flow would be out the front of the room so that when fairly large classes changed, there'd just be some going out, there'd be some coming in, and there'd be no conflict in the traffic.
But the people didn't go out the front.
So there was a lot of contact between the students going out the way they were not supposed to.
It was sort of like going up the down staircase.
But he had about everything that was available at that time in the classrooms.
And the console looked like a console on a 747.
It intimidated a lot of the faculty members.
But one of the things that Frank Hubert was set on was there would not be any overhead projectors in the Harrington classroom buildings.
But we had to go back later and add those because the faculty members weren't quite as progressive as Frank Hubert was.

But he had one classroom, classroom 100, where he had a telegraphic set up in there and it was designed so that the teacher could test as he was lecturing and the students could plug in the numbers and then in the back of the room he had a printout of how many students got the correct answer and all that.

So he was always very much on the cutting edge, and Frank Hubert was the prime mover, as far as I know, for the development of KAMU television, which is still, I think, probably the smallest public television station in the country.
Now, and do you happen to know when KAMU came on stream?
Well, it started out over in Bagley Hall.
Was it, was it in the Rudder days or the Williams?
Rudders, Rudder days.
Because in that old, you know, remember back in the old red brick building?
That was pretty bad.
But anyway, John Calhoun, you know, is obviously an engineer and a scientist.
And I think he did a lot and he and, he and Jack Williams I thought were
almost ideal co-leaders of the university, with Jack William with his history background and his more liberal arts type orientation, and John Calvin with his science and engineering.
And it was obvious to me, at least, that they had a lot of respect for each other.
Can you think of any strong disagreement
Not that I know of.
I never did.
Were you, did Williams by chance chat with you or anybody you know before he selected Calhoun?
No, not with me.
But you know, again, if you think about the establishment of the College of Medicine,
I think the Nautical Archaeology program, Institute of Nautical Archaeology was a real, real find for A&M.
We've gotten a lot of very positive public relations after that.
The Center for Tectonal Physics, I think John Calhoun was probably a major player in that.
So, and those were the things that built for a lot of our offshore technology.
The deep sea drilling program.
When you came over, yeah, everything was in T. Right.
You and Dick Winerdi.
Let's talk about Winerdi and his role.
Winerdi had been, I think, one of John Calhoun's graduate students.
Again, very bright, very creative thought process.
One thing I probably shouldn't say, but I enjoyed it, was one time Dick had this great revelation that what we needed was a war room.
And that every bit of information that did exist in the university should exist and be available in this war room.
And then whatever we needed to do.
Hi there.
Would you like a little light?
I can give you light.
But anyway, he met with some of us about doing all this, and Mel LaSalle and some others, because we had a lot of information, a lot more than most universities, I think, at that point in time.
One person who I had very little to do with, but I think was influential, was Andy Suttle.
The idea never had much to do with him.

But anyway, I remember telling Dick that the one thing I did understand about data is that someone has to input it, and someone has to be able to access it, and someone has to order it in a way that's meaningful.
And that what he was proposing to do would be absolutely wonderful to have, but it would be an overwhelming task.
But Dick, high energy.
like I said, innovative thought process.
May not be correct, but I didn't have the feeling that Dick was necessarily the stereotypical engineering's logical step-by-step process.
I think he could dream the great dream.
He and John Calhoun seemed to be a good pair and work together.
Do you remember Calhoun ever losing his temper?
Mr. No, I really don't.

But one of the things that, again, I think is important from my point of view, when there would be pretty serious disagreement between John Calhoun and someone else, most often an administrator, with the resolution, the thing that I said is kind of flippantly, but I never believed there was any hangover heat with John Calhoun that
that when you were through with one issue, the next issue started to even up.
And there are not many people who are capable of doing that.
There are some people who keep their own private school book.
And I never felt that was true of John Calvin.
And that if you were reasonably
Did you have any experience with them in the Austin side of the job?
Not a great deal.
But again, I think John Calhoun was viewed as someone who had a lot of integrity.
And I think generally across the board, A&M has had administrators who have been viewed to have integrity in dealing with people in Austin.
And I think that served A&M well.
And I think that, again, maybe because I want to believe it, but I think that A&M as an institution was less likely to confront the coordinating board
than maybe some other state-assisted universities did.
And I think A&M has probably generally been better off for having done that.
When there was a question about whether the recording board really had the authority to do it or not, I think A&M was more likely to go ahead and try to play by the rules as they understood them.
I think A&M was better served by that.
Uh, were you aware during William's last months that he was becoming physical?
Yes.
You could see him go down.
I mean, you could just, you could see him in one time, two weeks later, he was, he was obviously not as robust as he had been.
And one of the things that, uh, that really caught the attention, I don't know if you saw it or not, but soon after he died, KMU had
a series of events that Williams had participated in.
And when he came to A&M, he was so robust.
And then at the end, when they were showing clips, it was just dramatic how physically he was declining in his fitness.
All right.
So who was the interim president?
Well, Clyde Wells was.
Clyde Wells, yes.
Let's back up just a little bit.
Yeah, no.
Clyde Wells is the interim, and Williams goes to the hospital, and McCubbers comes back.
Right.
Okay.
We hear rumors about the board going to recreate the system administration.
Yes.
Can you throw in any light as to what you heard at that point about what was supposed to happen, going to happen, might happen?
Well, I tried to see anything but a little bit, but there were rumors at least that Clyde Wells would like to have that as a
I don't know.
I do feel certain that from the faculty's point of view, it was good that it did not become a public question.
But then there were questions about what would William's role be, who would be.
I think it was pretty well decided they would separate
the office and have a chancellor of the system and a president of the university.
And I think it was pretty well decided that Williams would be the chancellor for a while.
And then he would be the president.
And then that's when Jarvis became president, which came as a surprise to Hunter.
Hun?
Jeannie?
Would you get Hunter back in there please?
So I think there were a lot of us who thought, hoped that John Calhoun would be a serious candidate for president.
and Williams was chancellor and that would have been in many ways a continuation of what had been before with less demands on Williams.
And do you remember that first week after the choice was made by the board that Calhoun not be and Jarvis be the president?
The thing I remember most was Jarvis coming over and talking to Matt Prescott about being
and the vice president for active affairs.
The question of what my involvement would be if I would stay or go or whatever.
So I think that I guess Jarvis and Mac had known each other better than most of us had Jarvis because of Mac's involvement with teaching.
of agriculture, even though he was the dean of the College of Science, so.
Were you, did you have much interaction with Jarvis before that time?
No.
I had not.
No.
And as my memory fuzzy, that Calhoun moves out of the office over the weekend.
Yes.
And Jarvis is there Monday morning.
Right, with his staff.
Yeah.
And that you and I
And Linerdy are still there, but Linerdy quickly decides that he's got to- Do something else.
He's got to find another place.
Okay, then any changes in style with Mack and Jarvis, in administrative style?
Very much, they were very different styles from Calvin.
And again, not being limited by a lot of facts, Jarvis seemed to me to have very much of the agriculture style of leadership.
I think that they were more politically sensitive to a lot of things.
than had been the case with Dr. Kelly.
But there are so many interest groups involved in agriculture that you have to work with that I'm sure it's going to influence almost anyone's style.
Because commodity groups and producers and all kinds of people believe they deserve a lot of your attention.
We'd like to have a lot of involvement in decisions.
All right, we move back then over to the Koch building.
And who are the key members of Jarvis' office staff?
Glenn Dowling and Steve Pringle were there.
And what were their duties?
Glenn worked, I think, primarily with the budget aspect and some personnel things for Jarvis.
Steve seemed to be more involved with the political aspects of it.
I never really knew exactly what Steve was directly responsible for.
And I believe George also brought his own secretary from agriculture.
So he in essence brought his own staff.
And they obviously had already developed their own way of doing business.
And the rest of us had pretty well developed it, and so it was a transition period to try to meld the two styles.
And Steve did not stay very long.
Now, let's stop and look back on the Reuben period.
Can you think of any missed opportunities?
A lot of new things were done.
I think he seized most of the opportunities.
We had very rapid growth in graduate programs.
And one of the things that I liked and admired was that in many ways we didn't try to become the all comprehensive university.
And I think that's a tough thing for people not to want to do.
But basically we said we're going to continue to build on our strengths and we're going to try to develop some new strengths.
And graduate education is one of the real strengths.
Williams had a lot of charm.
